1. What is REST?

REST stands for Representational State Transfer. It’s an architectural style for designing
networked applications, especially web services. REST uses HTTP to communicate between
clients (like browsers or mobile apps) and servers.

Key Principles of REST:

(i) Statelessness :
Each request from a client to a server must contain all the information needed to understand
and process the request. The server does not store any client context between requests. This
makes REST scalable and simple to implement.

(ii) Client-Server Separation:
The client and server are independent. The client handles the user interface and user
experience, while the server manages data and business logic. This separation allows each side
to evolve independently.

(iii) Uniform Interface:
RESTful APIs use a consistent set of rules for communication. This includes using standard
HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) and predictable URLs. The uniform interface simplifies
interactions and integration.

(iv) Resource-Based:
Everything in REST is considered a resource (like a user, product, or order). Each resource is
 identified by a URL, and clients interact with resources using HTTP methods.

(v) Layered System:
REST allows for a layered architecture, where intermediaries (like proxies or gateways) can be
used between client and server without affecting their communication.

(vi) Cacheability:
Responses should indicate whether they can be cached. Caching improves performance and scalability.

Example:
A RESTful API for users might have endpoints like:

GET /users – Get all users
POST /users – Create a new user
GET /users/{id} – Get a specific user
PUT /users/{id} – Update a user
DELETE /users/{id} – Delete a user
These endpoints use HTTP methods to perform actions on resources (users) [1] [2].

2. What is a RESTful API?

A RESTful API is an API that follows the REST principles. It exposes resources via URLs and
allows clients to interact with them using HTTP methods.

Features:

a.Uses HTTP for communication
b.Follows statelessness and client-server separation
c.Provides a uniform interface
d.Uses standard HTTP status codes (200 OK, 404 Not Found, etc.)
e.Supports multiple formats (usually JSON or XML)

Why RESTful APIs?

(i)   Easy to use and integrate
(ii)  Scalable and flexible
(iii) Language-agnostic (works with any programming language)
(vi)  Widely adopted in industry

